      = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Costa Rica by cantons (Density).png\n| legend2         = Map of [[Cantons of Costa Rica|cantons]] with confirmed coronavirus cases (as of 15 April){{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201382}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Costa Rica]]\n| first_case      = [[Alajuela]]\n| dates           = Arrival: 22 February 2020 <br/> Confirmed: 6 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=6|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Tocumen International Airport]], [[Panama]] (first case) and [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] (first confirmed)\n| recovery_cases  = 196\n| severe_cases    = 7\n| deaths          = 6\n| confirmed_cases = 687\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1532-lineamientos-nacionales-para-la-vigilancia-de-la-infeccion-por-coronavirus-2019-ncov Ministerio de Salud]\n}}\nAn ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to Costa Rica on 6 March 2020, after a 49-year-old woman tourist from [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]], tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\":3\" /> Since then, as of 15 April 2020, 626 cases were confirmed in the country, causing 4 deaths, which represents the lowest death rate in Latin America at 0.5%.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Latest tally of cases in Latin America |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/covid-19-latest-tally-of-cases-in-latin-america/1806227 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr |agency=[[Anadolu Agency]] |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The pandemic has triggered a variety of responses from national to local governments, while also impacting politics, education and the economy.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nOn 22 February, a 54-year-old male Costa Rican citizen arrived from [[Tocumen International Airport]] in [[Panama]], he started to show symptoms on 28 February, and due to his work at the San Rafael Hospital in [[Alajuela]], a cluster was formed starting with some of his family members, patients and coworkers. It was treated as a suspicious case, and confirmed on 7 March.<ref name=\"1stcasepanama\">{{cite news |last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Melissa |title=Segundo caso sospechoso de coronavirus est\u00e1 grave en hospital p\u00fablico |url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/segundo-caso-sospechoso-de-coronavirus-esta-grave-en-hospital-publico |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"3march\" />\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn March 5, the Costa Rican [[Ministry of Health]] announced that it was investigating a possible first case of coronavirus in the country. It was a 52-year-old Costa Rican woman from the [[Pococ\u00ed (canton)|canton of Pococ\u00ed]], who visited [[Italy]] and [[Tunisia]] and returned to the country on February 29 without symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/salud-estudia-primer-caso-sospechoso-por-coronavirus-en-costa-rica|title=Salud estudia primer caso sospechoso por coronavirus en Costa Rica|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The pertinent tests were carried out on the woman and they were sent to the Costa Rican Institute of Research and Teaching in Nutrition and Health (Inciensa) to either rule out or confirm the case. However, this case was ruled out 24 hours after the test was performed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.repretel.com/actualidad/volvio-tranquilidad-pococi-descartarse-caso-coronavirus-179532|title=Volvi\u00f3 la tranquilidad a Pococ\u00ed tras descartarse caso de coronavirus|last=Repretel|website=Repretel|language=es|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the first case in Costa Rica was confirmed. The individual was a 49-year-old American woman who had arrived on a flight from [[New York City|New York]] on 1 March. She did not exhibit symptoms at the time. She was isolated in a [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]] lodging along with her husband who had also been in contact with infected persons in New York.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|accessdate=16 March 2020|title=Costa Rica reporta primer caso de coronavirus en Centroam\u00e9rica en una turista estadounidense|url=https://www.americaeconomia.com/politica-sociedad/mundo/costa-rica-reporta-primer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-centroamerica-en-una|newspaper=Am\u00e9ricaEconom\u00eda|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, four new cases were confirmed. One of them was directly related to the first case, both being US citizens who were visiting Costa Rica. The other cases are Costa Ricans.<ref name=\"3march\">{{cite news|accessdate=8 March 2020|title=Costa Rica confirms four new coronavirus cases|url=https://ticotimes.net/2020/03/07/costa-rica-confirms-four-new-coronavirus-cases|newspaper=Tico Times|date=7 March 2020|via=ticotimes.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March, another four new cases were confirmed, two of them were imported. Some patients were located at public hospitals while most of the foreign nationals remained at their respective hotels.<ref name=\"8march\">{{cite news|accessdate=9 March 2020|title=Because of Covid-19 cases CNE and Ministry of Health raise the sanitary alert level to yellow|url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1558-ante-casos-de-covid-19-cne-y-salud-elevan-alerta-sanitaria-a-alerta-amarilla|newspaper=Ministerio de Salud de Costa Rica|date=8 March 2020|via=ministeriodesalud.go.cr}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, a total of 22 confirmed cases was given by the Minister of Health of Costa Rica. 14 men and 8 women of which 19 are Costa Ricans (one of them a pregnant woman) and the other 3 are from other countries. They range from the ages of 10 to 73 years old.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/costa-rica-reporta-22-casos-confirmados-de-covid-19/ |title=Costa Rica reporta 22 casos confirmados de COVID-19 |work=crhoy.com |language=Spanish |date=11 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> It was also announced by the health authorities that there were confirmed cases in the Costa Rican cantons of [[Alajuela (canton)|Alajuela]], [[Escaz\u00fa (canton)|Escaz\u00fa]], [[Desamparados (canton)|Desamparados]], [[Grecia (canton)|Grecia]], [[Heredia (canton)|Heredia]], [[San Jos\u00e9 (canton)|San Jos\u00e9]], [[San Pablo (canton)|San Pablo]], [[Santa Cruz (canton), Costa Rica|Santa Cruz]] and [[Tib\u00e1s]].<ref>[https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/nueve-cantones-con-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus Nine cantons with confirmed cases of coronavirus] La Rep\u00fablica, 11 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, health authorities confirmed a total of 23 cases, the latest case is a local health care worker.<ref name=\"12march\">{{cite news|accessdate=12 March 2020|title=Costa Rica announces new measures to slow spread of coronavirus|url=https://ticotimes.net/2020/03/12/costa-rica-announces-new-measures-to-slow-spread-of-coronavirus|newspaper=Tico Times|date=12 March 2020|via=ticotimes.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the Ministry of Health confirmed 3 new cases, raising the total number of cases to 26, found in the provinces of [[San Jos\u00e9 Province|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Alajuela Province|Alajuela]], [[Heredia Province|Heredia]] and [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]], plus now the province of [[Cartago Province|Cartago]].<ref name=\"13march\">{{cite news|accessdate=13 March 2020|title=Costa Rica up to 26 confirmed coronavirus cases: Updates from Friday|url=https://ticotimes.net/2020/03/13/costa-rica-up-to-26-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-updates-from-friday|newspaper=Tico Times|date=13 March 2020|via=ticotimes.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the Costa Rican health authorities reported 8 more cases of the virus, for a total of 35. It was reported that there were 19 women and 16 infected men, of whom 30 were Costa Rican and 5 foreigners, with positive cases being registered in San Jos\u00e9, Heredia, Guanacaste, Alajuela and Cartago. The media reported 28 adults, 3 older adults and 4 infected minors were infected, while 450 tests have come back negative. A total of 350 educational centers have been closed down.<ref>[https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-35-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/ 35 cases of coronavirus are confirmed in Costa Rica] elmundo.cr, 15 March 2020</ref> Three patients were placed in ICU cubicles.<ref>[https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/llegan-a-35-los-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus Llegan a 35 los casos confirmados de coronavirus] larepublica.net, 15 March 2020</ref> Health authorities also confirmed cases in the cantons of [[Santa Ana (canton)|Santa Ana]], [[Grecia (canton)|Grecia]], [[Nicoya]], [[La Uni\u00f3n (canton)|La Uni\u00f3n]], [[Po\u00e1s (canton)|Po\u00e1s]], [[P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n (canton)|P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n]], [[San Pablo (canton)|San Pablo]] and [[Barva (canton)|Barva]].<ref>[https://delfino.cr/2020/03/covid-19-en-costa-rica COVID-19 en Costa Rica: 483 confirmados, 2 fallecidos, 24 recuperados, 5042 descartados] La Rep\u00fablica, 15 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the Health Minister confirmed 41 cases of coronavirus in the country.<ref name=\"16march\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-41-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 41 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=16 March 2020|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the Costa Rican health authorities reported 9 new cases. The number of infected women rose to 24 and the number of men to 26, of which 44 are Costa Rican and 6 are foreigners. In addition, the number of negative tests rose to 720. New cases were confirmed in the cantons of [[Cartago (canton)|Cartago]] and [[Curridabat (canton)|Curridabat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/municipales/estos-son-los-19-cantones-con-casos-positivos-de-coronavirus/|title=Estos son los 19 cantones con casos positivos de coronavirus|last=Canales|first=Danny|date=17 March 2020|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 19 more cases were confirmed for a total of 69. Cases were confirmed in 30 women and 39 men, of whom 63 are Costa Rican and 6 foreign, and of whom 57 represent adults, 7 senior citizens and 5 minors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-69-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 69 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=18 March 2020|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Cases were also confirmed in the cantons of [[Goicoechea (canton)|Goicoechea]], [[Moravia (canton)|Moravia]], [[Santo Domingo Canton (Costa Rica)|Santo Domingo]], and [[Santa B\u00e1rbara (canton)|Santa B\u00e1rbara]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Estos son los 25 cantones donde se confirmaron casos de COVID-19|website=CRHoy|language=es|url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/estos-son-los-25-cantones-donde-se-confirmaron-casos-de-covid-19/}}</ref>\n\nOne senior citizen, an 87-year-old man, died on 18 March and is the first COVID-19 death in Costa Rica. He was one of 25 people infected by a doctor in Alajuela.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/confirman-primera-muerte-por-covid-19-en-costa-rica/|title=Confirman primera muerte por COVID-19 en Costa Rica {{!}} Crhoy.com|website=CRHoy.com {{!}} Periodico Digital {{!}} Costa Rica Noticias 24/7|language=es|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, 18 more cases were confirmed for a total of 87. Infected people were found in an age range between 2 and 87 years. There were 35 women and 52 men, of whom 79 are Costa Rican and 8 foreigners. The first case was also announced in the province of [[Lim\u00f3n Province|Lim\u00f3n]], in the [[Lim\u00f3n (canton)|canton]] of the same name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-87-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 87 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=19 March 2020|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On the afternoon of 19 March, the Ministry of Health announced two more cases for a total of 89, these in [[Quesada, San Carlos|Ciudad Quesada]], in the canton of [[San Carlos (canton)|San Carlos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teletica.com/251991_coronavirus-salud-da-a-conocer-dos-casos-mas-positivos-y-el-total-es-de-89-enfermos|title=Coronavirus: Salud confirma dos casos m\u00e1s, el total sube a 89 {{!}} Teletica|website=www.teletica.com|language=es|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLater, on 19 March, the health authorities announced the second death of a patient with Coronavirus in Costa Rica. It was an older adult, of 87 years old, and resident of Alajuela.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirma-segundo-fallecido-por-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirma segundo fallecido por coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=20 March 2020|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the Ministry of Health confirmed a total of 113 cases, adding a total of 24 more cases. The Ministry also reported the recovery of the first two patients with the virus, who were the two American tourists who were isolated in a hotel in San Jos\u00e9. New cases were also reported in the cantons of [[V\u00e1squez de Coronado (canton)|V\u00e1squez de Coronado]] and [[Montes de Oca (canton)|Montes de Oca]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.teletica.com/252063_costa-rica-reporta-113-casos-de-covid-19?fbclid=IwAR0DuujSrxZe2HCge2Xazfz3eRep4VOaVW2eWcfFVvIYgqya27OoFztw4tg|title=Costa Rica reporta 113 casos de Covid-19 {{!}} Teletica|website=www.teletica.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, health authorities reported only 4 more cases for a total of 117. This is the lowest number of new confirmed cases since 15 March. In addition, the number of negative tests rose to 1,190.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://delfino.cr/2020/03/cuatro-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19-en-costa-rica-total-sube-a-117|title=Cuatro nuevos casos de COVID-19 en Costa Rica; total sube a 117|website=delfino.cr|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the Ministry of Health reported an increase of 17 cases, giving a total of 134, of which 55 represent women and 79 men, and of which 117 are Costa Rican and 17 foreigners, all with an age range between 2 and 87 years. These cases included the first case in [[Aserr\u00ed (canton)|Aserr\u00ed]] and the first case in the province of [[Puntarenas Province|Puntarenas]], this one in the city of [[San Vito (Costa Rica)|San Vito]], [[Coto Brus (canton)|Coto Brus]] canton. There are also 1,400 people who tested negative and 9 people in hospitals, three of them in intensive care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://delfino.cr/2020/03/17-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19-en-costa-rica-total-sube-a-134|title=17 nuevos casos de COVID-19 en Costa Rica; total sube a 134|website=delfino.cr|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Costa Rica medical cases chart}}On 23 March, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 158 confirmed cases, an increase of 24 cases. 68 women and 90 men have contracted the disease.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/actualizacion-158-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica|title=Actualizaci\u00f3n: 158 casos confirmados de coronavirus en Costa Rica, se cierran playas y templos|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the health authorities reported an increase of 19 cases for a total of 177. It was reported that the cases comprised people between 2 and 87 years of age, of which 103 are men and 74 are women. 159 are Costa Rican and 18 foreigners. It was also reported that there are 6 people hospitalized, of which 4 are in intensive care. Lastly, the number of negative tests rose to 1,619. The cantons of [[Jim\u00e9nez (canton)|Jim\u00e9nez]], [[Liberia (canton)|Liberia]] and [[Montes de Oro (canton)|Montes de Oro]] reported their first cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/dia-19-de-emergencia-por-nuevo-coronavirus-17/OFRDSOFRRBCMXO3YZLBMPH4EDE/story/|title=D\u00eda 19 de emergencia por nuevo coronavirus en Costa Rica: Gobierno suspende aumento salarial; 177 casos confirmados|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, a total of 201 cases were reported, for an increase of 24. Of the reported cases, 183 represent Costa Ricans and 18 foreigners. There were 65 more negative results bringing the total to 1,684. The first cases were reported in the cantons of [[Orotina (canton)|Orotina]], [[Alvarado (canton)|Alvarado]], [[Bel\u00e9n (canton)|Bel\u00e9n]], [[Flores (canton)|Flores]], [[Puntarenas (canton)|Puntarenas]] and [[Garabito (canton)|Garabito]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/coronavirus-en-costa-rica-cifra-supera-los-200-casos-confirmados|title=Coronavirus en Costa Rica: cifra total supera los 200 casos confirmados|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 231 confirmed cases, an increase of 31. Of the reported cases, 101 represent women and 130 men, of which 209 are Costa Rican and 18 foreigners. In addition, the number of negative tests rose to 2,331, and 8 cases were being analyzed for discharge. The first cases were reported in the cantons of [[Valverde Vega (canton)|Sarch\u00ed]], [[Oreamuno (canton)|Oreamuno]], [[El Guarco (canton)|El Guarco]] and [[Tilar\u00e1n (canton)|Tilar\u00e1n]]. Lastly, 5 people were reported to be in intensive care in hospitals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/nuevo-coronavirus-en-costa-rica-231-enfermos/Q2J3CFPHIVHIZEF7GKLF7KM7QQ/story/|title=Nuevo coronavirus en Costa Rica: 231 enfermos dispersos en m\u00e1s de la mitad de los cantones|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> A total of 22 health care workers have contracted the virus so far.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/neurocirujanos-del-hospital-mexico-estan-aislados-por-covid-19/|title=Neurocirujanos del Hospital M\u00e9xico est\u00e1n aislados por COVID-19|website=CRHoy.com|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the health authorities reported an increase of 32 cases, for a total of 263, this being the day with the highest number of confirmed cases since the virus arrived in the country. Of the reported cases, 121 represented women and 142 men, of whom 241 are Costa Rican and 20 foreigners. In addition, a total of 2,786 tests have been negative, and another patient recovered, for a total of 3 recoveries. The first cases were reported in the cantons of [[Tarraz\u00fa (canton)|Tarraz\u00fa]], [[Mora (canton)|Mora]], [[San Ram\u00f3n (canton)|San Ram\u00f3n]] and [[Carrillo (canton)|Carrillo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/nuevo-coronavirus-en-costa-rica-263-contagiados/FZQ5GHJCOZHXJJK3JAFP4FSF7Y/story/|title=Nuevo coronavirus en Costa Rica: 263 contagiados; se ampliar\u00e1 restricci\u00f3n fines de semana de 8 p. m. a 5 a. m.|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a total of 295 cases were reported, an increase of 32. Of the reported cases, 157 represent men and 138 women, of which 272 are Costa Rican, 21 foreigners and 2 are under investigation. A total of 2,912 negative tests and 9 hospitalized patients were reported, plus 6 in intensive care. So far 52 health workers of the Costa Rican Social Security Fund (C[[Costa Rican Social Security Fund|aja Costarricense del Seguro Social]] or CCSS) have contracted the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Salud reporta 295 casos de Covid-19, aumentan pacientes hospitalizados|website=Teletica.com|language=es|url=https://www.teletica.com/253709_salud-reporta-295-casos-de-covid-19-aumentan-pacientes-hospitalizados}}</ref> The first cases were reported in the cantons of [[Alajuelita (canton)|Alajuelita]], [[Turrubares (canton)|Turrubares]] and [[Naranjo (canton)|Naranjo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.presidencia.go.cr/comunicados/2020/03/sube-cantidad-de-pacientes-covid-19-internados-y-en-cuidados-intensivos-15-en-total/|title=Sube cantidad de pacientes COVID-19 internados y en cuidados intensivos: 15 en total|website=Presidencia de la Rep\u00fablica de Costa Rica|language=es|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 314 confirmed cases, for an increase of 19. Of the reported cases, 164 represented men and 150 women, of which 290 are Costa Rican and 24 foreigners. There have been 3115 negative tests, and 13 people have been hospitalized. The first case was also reported in the [[Osa (canton)|canton of Osa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elperiodicocr.com/costa-rica-alcanza-los-314-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Costa Rica alcanza los 314 casos confirmados de coronavirus COVID-19 {{!}} El Peri\u00f3dicocr.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, health authorities announced an increase of 16 cases, for a total of 330. Cases included 170 males and 160 females, 303 are Costa Ricans and 27 are foreign nationals; 293 are adults, 24 are senior citizens, plus 13 minors. Out of 3,692 tests, 8.9 percent have been positive and the rest (3,362)  have been negative. One patient has recovered, for a total of 4 recoveries. The Minister of Health warned that the country had just started climbing the curve of cases.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ministro de Salud: Estamos empezando a subir la curva|language=es|website=Costa Rica Noticias|url=http://www.costaricanoticias.cr/detalle/7201/ministro-de-salud:-estamos-empezando-a-subir-la-curva}}</ref> The first case was reported in [[San Isidro (canton)|canton of San Isidro]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=52 cantones reportan COVID-19: hoy se sum\u00f3 San Isidro de Heredia|date=30 March 2020|language=es|url=https://observador.cr/noticia/52-cantones-reportan-covid-19-hoy-se-sumo-san-isidro-de-heredia/}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the Minister of Health reported a total of 347 cases, an increase of 17. Cases consisted of 180 males and 167 females, 320 were Costa Ricans and 27 were foreign nationals. They ruled 3,498 cases as negative, and the number of patients hospitalized rose to 15, 8 of whom were in intensive care.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Se confirman 347 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|language=es|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-347-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|website=El Mundo CR|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 375 confirmed cases, for an increase of 28. Of the reported cases, 194 represent men and 181 women, of which 346 are Costa Rican and 29 foreigners. In addition, a total of 3,843 negative tests were reported. The first case was also presented in the [[Esparza (canton)|canton of Esparza]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/coronavirus-en-costa-rica-gobierno-socara-medidas/V27TKSE5XZBLLJKLDS4Q2J4SEA/story/|title=Coronavirus en Costa Rica: Gobierno ampl\u00eda restricci\u00f3n vehicular para Semana Santa contra covid-19|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the health authorities reported an increase of 21 cases, for a total of 396. Of the reported cases, 204 represent men and 192 women, of whom 366 are Costa Rican and 30 foreign, and of whom 356 are adults, 26 older adults and 14 minors. A total of 3,954 tests have been found negative, and 2 more patients recovered, for a total of 6. An increase in the number of hospitalized to 17 was also reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-han-recuperado-6-personas-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se han recuperado 6 personas de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-02|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, a total of 416 cases were reported, an increase of 20. Of these, 215 represent men and 201 women, of whom 385 are Costa Rican and 31 foreigners. There were 4,044 tests ruled negative, and the number of hospitalized people increased to 23, of whom 13 were in intensive care. Five more people were declared as recovered, for a total of 11. The first case was also presented in the [[Hojancha (canton)|canton of Hojancha.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-416-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 416 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-03|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 435 confirmed cases, for an increase of 19. Of these cases, 223 represent men and 212 women, of which 404 are Costa Rican and 31 foreigners. In addition, a total of 4,219 negative tests were reported. Two more people were declared as recovered, for a total of 13. The first case was also presented in the [[Para\u00edso (canton)|canton of Para\u00edso]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/aumenta-a-435-cifra-de-confirmados-con-coronavirus|title=Aumenta a 435 cifra de confirmados con Coronavirus|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the health authorities reported an increase of 19 cases, for a total of 454. Of the reported cases, 232 represent men and 222 women, of whom 423 are Costa Rican and 31 foreigners. The confirmed cases consist of 411 adults, 28 seniors and 15 minors. A total of 4,644 negative tests were reported and 3 more patients were declared as recovered, for a total of 16. An increase in the number of hospitalized was also reported to 26, of which 14 were in intensive care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/covid-19-en-costa-rica-19-enfermos-mas-elevan-a/3PD3DWIUL5BEFEUM2AMV6MWPZU/story/|title=Covid-19 en Costa Rica: 19 enfermos m\u00e1s elevan a 454 los casos confirmados este 5 de abril|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, a total of 467 cases were reported, an increase of 13. Of these, 240 represent men and 227 women, of whom 435 are Costa Rican and 32 foreigners. 4896 discarded cases were reported. Two more people were declared as recovered, for a total of 18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-467-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 467 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-06|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 483 confirmed cases, for an increase of 16. Of these, 246 represent men and 237 women, of which 449 are Costa Rican and 34 foreigners. In addition, a total of 5042 discarded cases were reported and the number of hospitalized persons increased to 25. Six more people were declared as recovered, for a total of 24. The first case was also presented in the [[Turrialba (canton)|canton of Turrialba]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-483-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 483 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-07|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the health authorities reported an increase of 19 cases, for a total of 502. Of the reported cases, 259 represent men and 243 women, of which 468 are Costa Rican and 34 foreign, and of which 455 are adults, 29 older adults and 18 minors. A total of 5533 discarded cases were reported and five more were declared as recovered, for a total of 29. A decrease in the number of hospitalized was also reported to 23, of which 15 were in intensive care. The first recovery of an intensive care patient in the country was also reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://delfino.cr/2020/04/ccss-sobre-alta-de-paciente-que-estuvo-en-uci-hoy-es-un-dia-de-mucha-alegria-para-el-pais|title=CCSS sobre alta de paciente que estuvo en UCI: \"Hoy es un d\u00eda de mucha alegr\u00eda para el pa\u00eds\"|website=delfino.cr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn the afternoon of April 8, the Ministry of Health confirmed the third death of a patient with Coronavirus in Costa Rica. It was a 45-year-old man, without risk factors, and a resident of San Jos\u00e9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/salud/hombre-de-45-anos-sin-factores-de-riesgo-es-el/MHKBOSSYIFBYJL6LMYD72ROCE4/story/|title=Tercer muerto por coronavirus en Costa Rica: Hombre de 45 a\u00f1os sin factores de riesgo|last=E|first=Daniela Cerdas|website=La Naci\u00f3n, Grupo Naci\u00f3n|language=es-LA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, a total of 539 cases were reported, an increase of 37, the highest number of confirmed cases on the same day to date. Of these, 280 represent men and 259 women, of whom 505 are Costa Rican and 34 foreigners. 5759 discarded cases were reported and one more person was declared as recovered, for a total of 30. The number of hospitalized patients decreased to 19. The first case was also presented in the [[Siquirres (canton)|canton of Siquirres]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-539-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 539 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-09|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 558 confirmed cases, for an increase of 19. Of these cases, 289 represent men and 269 women, of which 524 are Costa Rican and 34 foreigners. In addition, a total of 5894 cases were discarded and the number of hospitalized persons increased to 20, of which 13 were found in intensive care. Twelve others were declared as recovered, for a total of 42. The first case was also presented in the [[Puriscal (canton)|canton of Puriscal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-558-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 558 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-10|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the health authorities reported an increase of 19 cases, for a total of 577. Of the reported cases, 300 represent men and 277 women, of whom 541 are Costa Rican and 36 foreign, and of whom 526 are adults, 31 older adults and 20 minors. A total of 6031 discarded cases were reported and seven more were declared as recovered, for a total of 49. A decrease in the number of hospitalized patients was also reported to 18. The first case was also presented in the canton of Pococ\u00ed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/actualizacion|title=19 casos nuevos de Coronavirus en Costa Rica para un total de 577|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, a total of 595 cases were reported, an increase of 18. Of these, 310 represent men and 285 women, of whom 557 are Costa Rican and 38 foreigners. A total of 6167 cases were discarded and seven more were declared as recovered, for a total of 56. The number of hospitalized patients increased to 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/18-casos-nuevos-de-coronavirus-y-costa-rica-llega-a-595-personas-infectadas|title=18 casos nuevos de Coronavirus y Costa Rica llega a 595 personas infectadas|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, the Ministry of Health reported a total of 612 confirmed cases, for an increase of 17. Of these, 317 represent men and 295 women, of which 569 are Costa Rican and 43 foreigners. In addition, a total of 6,256 cases were discarded and the number of hospitalized persons increased to 20, of which 14 were found in intensive care. Seven more people were declared as recovered, for a total of 62.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/17-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica-para-un-total-de-612|title=17 nuevos casos de Coronavirus en Costa Rica, para un total de 612|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the health authorities reported an increase of 6 cases, for a total of 618, the lowest number of confirmed cases on the same day since March 21. Of the reported cases, 320 represent men and 298 women, of whom 575 are Costa Rican and 43 foreigners, and of whom 562 are adults, 31 older adults and 25 minors. A total of 6326 discarded cases were reported and four more were declared as recovered, for a total of 66. A decrease in the number of hospitalized was also reported to 19, of which 13 were in intensive care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-618-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 618 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-14|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, a total of 626 cases were reported, an increase of 8. Of these, 324 represent men and 302 women, of which 570 are Costa Rican and 43 foreigners. A total of 6511 cases were discarded and one more person was declared as recovered, for a total of 67. The number of hospitalized patients decreased to 16, of which 11 were in intensive care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/se-confirman-626-casos-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica/|title=Se confirman 626 casos de coronavirus en Costa Rica|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-15|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The Ministry also reported a cluster of cases in a CCSS call center in San Jos\u00e9, where up to 31 cases of COVID-19 were reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/un-conglomerado-de-casos-de-coronavirus-esta-en-un-call-center-de-san-jose|title=Un conglomerado de casos de Coronavirus est\u00e1 en un call center de San Jos\u00e9|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of April 15, the Ministry of Health confirmed the fourth death of a patient with COVID-19 in Costa Rica. It was an 84-year-old man, with risk factors, and who was admitted to the San Juan de Dios Hospital, in San Jos\u00e9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/se-confirma-la-cuarta-muerte-de-coronavirus-en-costa-rica|title=Se confirma la cuarta muerte por Coronavirus en Costa Rica|website=www.larepublica.net|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, a total of 642 cases were reported, an increase of 16 from the previous day.\n\n== Government response ==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 8 March, the Costa Rican Ministry of Health and the National Emergency Committee (CNE) raised the sanitary alert level to yellow.<ref name=\"8march\" />\n\nOn 11 March, the [[University of Costa Rica]] ordered its teachers to suspend all face-to-face classes and implement a virtual teaching modality.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=15 March 2020|title=Confirmed: UCR orders teachers to teach virtual classes|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/ucr-pide-a-docentes-impartir-clases-virtuales|newspaper=La Rep\u00fablica|date=11 March 2020|via=larepublica.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the Minister of Health stated Costa Rica will not close its borders to international visitors at that time.<ref name=\"12march\" />\nThe CNE has launched the brand new 1322 COVID-19 help line.<ref name=\"13march\" /> Leaders of [[Belize]], Costa Rica, [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Panama]], and the [[Dominican Republic]] signed an agreement for dealing with the coronavirus [[pandemic]]. It includes canceling the Costa Rican film festival.<ref>[https://ticotimes.net/2020/03/13/central-america-agrees-to-regional-plan-vs-coronavirus-costa-rican-film-festival-suspended Central America agrees to regional plan vs. coronavirus; Costa Rican film festival suspended] AFP and The Tico Times, 13 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the Ministry of Education of Costa Rica decided to temporarily suspend lessons in a total of 317 educational centers, representing 7% of Costa Rica's educational centers. Closures included educational centers with confirmed cases of COVID-19, all public schools for special education, educational centers belonging to the same school circuit as the educational center where a confirmed case was identified, and educational centers that have been affected by prolonged water rationing.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=15 March 2020|title=Confirmed: Ministry of Education lists 317 educational centers that suspend lessons|url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/ministerio-de-educacion-suspende-lecciones-en-317-centros-educativos|newspaper=La Rep\u00fablica|date=13 March 2020|via=larepublica.net}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, an executive agreement between the President of the Republic, [[Carlos Alvarado Quesada]], and the Minister of Health, Daniel Salas, granted health authority to the members of the Costa Rican Public Force (the police enforcement agency) for the surveillance and control of the virus, both to verify the closure of bars, clubs and casinos, as well as to ensure 50% of visiting capacity for the other meeting centers. Businesses that do not comply with the new sanitary policy will be subject of a 30 day long closure.<ref>[https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/ministerio-de-salud-anuncia-cierre-de-todos-los-bares-discotecas-y-casinos/ Ministerio de Salud anuncia cierre de todos los bares, discotecas y casinos] elmundo.cr, 15 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the government also decreed a '''state of national emergency''', due to the threat of the virus after being present in the country for only 10 days. In addition, lessons were suspended in all public and private schools and colleges until 4 April. Access to the country was also reduced to only Costa Ricans and permanent residents, a measure that will start a minute after midnight on 18 March and last until 12 April. Those entering must remain in quarantine for at least 14 days.<ref name=\"16march\" />\n\nOn 20 March, after the school kitchen workers refused to serve students, the Ministry of Public Education (MEP) agreed on delivering food packages to the parents of their students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teletica.com/252065_mep-entregara-paquetes-de-comida-ante-cierre-de-comedores-estudiantiles|title=MEP entregar\u00e1 paquetes de comida ante cierre de comedores estudiantiles {{!}} Teletica|access-date=2020-03-21|website=www.teletica.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the Ministry of Health and the Government announced new prevention measures against the virus, including the total closure of beaches in the country, the mandatory closure of temples and religious services, and vehicle restriction in the main cities of the country from 10 p.m. to 5 a.m.. All residents and refugees will lose their migratory status if they leave the country for any reason.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn 24 March, the government announced they will temporarily reduce their in person workforce by 80% and also void the salary raise approved last January for all public servants except for the police force.<ref>[https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1584-gobierno-anuncia-medidas-laborales-en-el-sector-publico-para-combatir-el-covid-19 Gobierno anuncia medidas laborales en el sector p\u00fablico para combatir el COVID-19] Health Ministry, 24 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the Finance Minister discussed a bill that the government would be presenting later on. This bill would mean the creation of a solidarity tax that would be deducted from all workers' salaries that earned more than \u00a2 500.000. Its goal was helping people impacted by the Covid-19 crisis. Hours later president Carlos Alvarado published that he would not support that bill and stated that \"Plan Proteger\" consisted of protecting the unemployed and workers already impacted by salary reductions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Presidente desmiente a Ministro de Hacienda: No habr\u00e1 impuesto a salarios mayores a \u20a1500 mil|url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/presidente-desmiente-a-ministro-de-hacienda-no-habra-impuesto-a-salarios-mayores-a-%e2%82%a1500-mil/}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the Government announced the extension of the sanitary vehicle restriction on weekends from 8 p.m. until 5 a.m. In addition, the Government announced that it was evaluating the implementation of a temporary solidarity tax on wages above \u00a2 1.1 million, a measure that would raise up to \u00a2 25,000 million per month, however, the Government announced that other sources of income will be processed and that it will present an extraordinary budget of \u00a2 225,000 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ameliarueda.com/nota/gobierno-valora-impuesto-solidario-a-salarios-superiores-de-1-millon|title=Gobierno valora impuesto solidario a salarios superiores de \u00a21,1 mill\u00f3n, anuncia Alvarado|last=Alfaro|first=Josue|website=ameliarueda.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the Minister of Health Daniel Salas announced they would be imposing a new sanitary restriction for all businesses with sanitary permits that serve the public. This measure would begin at 8 p.m. weekends, starting that very same day.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sube cantidad de pacientes COVID-19 internados y en cuidados intensivos: 15 en total|website=Ministerio de Salud|url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1589-sube-cantidad-de-pacientes-covid-19-internados-y-en-cuidados-intensivos-15-en-total}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the Ministry of Health sent a bill to the Asamblea Legislativa, the Costa Rican Congress. This bill pretended to reform the article 378 of the Ley General de Salud (General Health Act) in order to impose fines for violating the sanitary restriction or the quarantine, ranging from 1 through 5 base salaries.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Multa por incumplir cuarentena ser\u00eda de m\u00e1s de \u00a2 2 millones|website=CRHoy.com|url=https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/multa-por-incumplir-cuarentena-seria-de-mas-de-2-millones/}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the government announced the opening of the new Centro Especializado de Atenci\u00f3n de Pacientes con COVID-19 (CEACO), a center specialized in Covid-19 patients at the facilities of CENARE. It reinforced the services provided by the Caja Costarricense de Seguro Social (CCSS) in Costa Rica by treating up to 88 Covid-19 patients in intermediate or continuing care units.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.presidencia.go.cr/comunicados/2020/03/ccss-refuerza-red-de-servicios-para-atencion-covid-19-con-nuevo-centro/|title=CCSS refuerza red de servicios para atenci\u00f3n COVID-19 con nuevo centro|access-date=2020-03-31|website=Presidencia de la Rep\u00fablica de Costa Rica}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn April 1, with [[Holy Week]] and [[Easter]] approaching, the government announced new measures to contain the spread of COVID-19 during this time when people are used to going out and vacationing. The main measure was to extend the night driving restriction from Friday, April 3 and until Tuesday, April 7, from 5:00&nbsp;p.m. to 5:00&nbsp;a.m. throughout the country. Long-distance public transport will also be restricted, and establishments with sanitary operating permits and attention to face-to-face public will be closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1594-en-el-marco-de-la-semana-santa-gobierno-refuerza-medidas-para-contener-el-contagio-por-el-covid-19?fbclid=IwAR32EO-F2FKbsz_JCrBkkoR1uoenE8jB4UKTsSZntX4iXhYKc9s-18pgKRo|title=En el marco de la Semana Santa Gobierno refuerza medidas para contener el contagio por el COVID-19|date=1 April 2020|work=Ministerio de Salud P\u00fablica de Costa Rica|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Legislative Assembly]] approved two bills to increase the fines for noncompliance with sanitary orders and vehicle restriction. Fines ranging from \u20a1450,000 (US$780) to \u20a12.2 million (US$3,800) would be applied if a person having risk factors and being a suspected or confirmed case of the disease fails to comply with the isolation order. In the case of the traffic law reform, drivers could be subject to a fine of \u20a1107,000 (US$185), a loss of six points on their license, and removal of license plates if they violate the restriction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/aprueban-leyes-en-primer-debate-para-aumentar-multas-por-incumplir-restriccion-vehicular-y-orden-sanitaria/|title=Aprueban leyes en primer debate para aumentar multas por incumplir restricci\u00f3n vehicular y orden sanitaria|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-01|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the Government announced the launch of an economic bonus for those workers affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. The bonus varies between \u20a1 125 thousand per month for people laid off or with a workday reduced to 50% or more, and \u20a1 62 thousand 500 per month for those who have reduced their workday by 50% or less.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.cr/costa-rica/gobierno-lanza-bono-economico-para-trabajadores-afectados-por-covid-19/|title=Gobierno lanza bono econ\u00f3mico para trabajadores afectados por COVID-19|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Karla P\u00e9rez|date=2020-04-09|website=El Mundo CR|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n\nBy 25 March, the Chamber of Commerce and the Federation of Business Chambers of the Central American Isthmus reported that around 3% of the companies have reduced their workforce, with such figure projected to grow to 55% in a month. Other projections forecast an 18% of suspended operations and 11% of definitive closures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gudi\u00f1o |first1=Ronny |title=El 3% de empresas ha reducido su personal |url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/el-3-de-empresas-han-reducido-su-personal |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Hospitality businesses ===\n\nOn 25 March, the Costar Rica Institute of Tourism declared the tourism sector in a total emergency and calamity state; a zero visitors season is expected for at least three months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gudi\u00f1o |first1=Ronny |title=\"Sector se encuentra en estado de emergencia total\": Instituto Costarricense de Turismo |url=https://www.larepublica.net/noticia/sector-se-encuentra-en-estado-de-emergencia-total-instituto-costarricense-de-turismo |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the Chamber of Restaurants and Bars of Costa Rica (CACORE) reported 109,000 laid off workers, and 42% (7,980) of the affiliated businesses were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solano |first1=Johel |title=109 mil ticos despedidos tras el cierre de 8 mil bares y restaurantes |url=https://www.crhoy.com/economia/109-mil-ticos-fueron-despedidos-ante-el-cierre-de-8-mil-bares-y-restaurantes/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n=== By region ===\nAs of 22 April 2020, there were 681 confirmed cases in Costa Rica along with 6 deaths and 180 recoveries. The following table shows the confirmed COVID-19 cases by province and canton in Costa Rica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/0/viewer?mid=1Exx7FD-7DU5TvMzPs-UBl0wXbeQtToc-&ll=9.725917292852644%2C-83.49896475465675&z=8|title=Mapa del coronavirus en Costa Rica: casos por cant\u00f3n|date=2020|website=Ministerio de Salud P\u00fablica|publisher=Ministerio de Salud P\u00fablica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lineamientos Nacionales para la Vigilancia de la infecci\u00f3n por Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1532-lineamientos-nacionales-para-la-vigilancia-de-la-infeccion-por-coronavirus-2019-ncov |website=www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:92%\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Province\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Canton\n! colspan=\"2\" |Cases\n! colspan=\"2\" |Recoveries\n! colspan=\"2\" |Deaths\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50px;\